# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: amazake
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:amazake/agedashi-dōfu] While *agedashi dōfu* is the best-known *agedashi* dish, some other dishes may be prepared with similar techniques.
[src:amazake/agedashi-dōfu] These include *agedashinasu* (揚げ出し茄子), using eggplant.
[src:amazake/alpro] Alpro was founded in 1980, as a subsidiary of the Vandemoortele Groep, which is based in Belgium.
[src:amazake/alpro] Alpro expanded across Europe and in 2000 built a soy milk plant in Burton Latimer, England.
[src:amazake/alpro] In 2008, Alpro launched the UK's first "reduced calorie soya alternative to yogurt" following the introduction of its Soy Light "reduced calorie soya milk" in 2006.
[src:amazake/alpro] Alpro's revenues are reported to have tripled during the period from 2000 to 2008.
[src:amazake/alpro] In 2009, beverages made up two-thirds of Alpro's revenues.
[src:amazake/alpro] In June 2009, Vandemoortele sold Alpro for an estimated US$455 million to Dean Foods, which marketed the "Silk" soy milk brand in the US.
[src:amazake/alpro] In June 2013, WhiteWave, the Dean Foods subsidiary that managed Alpro, was spun-off as an independent company – listing on the New York Stock Exchange.
[src:amazake/alpro] In July 2013, Dean Foods sold their remaining 19.9% stake in WhiteWave, thus ending their involvement with Alpro.
[src:amazake/alpro] In July 2016, it was announced that the French company Danone would purchase WhiteWave Foods for $10.4 billion.
[src:amazake/alpro] The acquisition was completed in April 2017 and newly formed company is named "DanoneWave".
[src:amazake/alpro] In 2020, Alpro's *No Sugars* oatmilk won the Lausanne Index Prize – Supreme Award, a processed food prize.
[src:amazake/alpro] Alpro distributes soya based vegan products under the brands *Belsoy*, *Alpro Soya* and *Provamel*.
[src:amazake/alpro] Products include soya milk, soy yogurt, soya cream and soya based desserts, plant-based margarines and plant-based ice cream.
[src:amazake/alpro] All products are made from either non-GM soya, almonds, hazelnuts, cashew, rice, oats or coconut.
[src:amazake/alpro] The Provamel brand is reserved exclusively for organic products (including many organic versions of Alpro Soya products), which are intended for sale only by independent health food retailers.
[src:amazake/alpro] Alpro soya milk scored best (out of 16 tested different plain soy milks), when rated by Germany's leading consumer safety group Stiftung Warentest.
[src:amazake/alpro] Other Alpro products include yogurt as well as "dessert and meat alternative products".
[src:amazake/alpro] To demonstrate Alpro's milk and yogurt alternatives, a year-long experiential marketing campaign gave consumers in the UK the opportunity to sample the breakfast menu products at various events and shopping centres around the country.
[src:amazake/alpro] Alpro also encouraged visitors to have their photo taken at the internet pod on the stand and upload it to Facebook, thereby joining the Alpro Soya Facebook page.
[src:amazake/amacha] This tea contains tannin and phyllodulcin, a sweetener 400–800 times sweeter than table sugar (sucrose) or 2 times sweeter than saccharin.
[src:amazake/amacha] The beverage is credited with antiallergic properties.
[src:amazake/amacha] It is also used in the prevention of periodontitis.
[src:amazake/amacha] This tea is often used in ceremonies celebrating Buddha's Birthday, in Japanese Buddhism on April 8.
[src:amazake/amacha] At that occasion, Japanese people pour amacha on small Buddha statues decorated with flowers, as if bathing a newborn baby.
[src:amazake/amanattō] Amanattō was originally called *amananattō* (甘名納糖); the name was abbreviated to *amanattō* after World War II.
[src:amazake/amanattō] The resemblance of the name to the fermented bean dish nattō is coincidental.
[src:amazake/amanattō] In Hokkaidō, amanattō is used in cooking *sekihan*.
[src:amazake/amanattō] For this reason, unlike other areas in East Asia, the *sekihan* of Hokkaidō is a little sweet.
[src:amazake/amazake] There are several recipes for *amazake* that have been used for hundreds of years.
[src:amazake/amazake] By a popular recipe, *kōji* is added to cooled whole grain rice causing enzymes to break down the carbohydrates into simpler unrefined sugars.
[src:amazake/amazake] As the mixture incubates, sweetness develops naturally.
[src:amazake/amazake] By another recipe, sake kasu is mixed with water and sugar is added.
[src:amazake/amazake] Similar beverages include the Chinese *jiuniang* which is more pudding like and Korean *gamju* or *sikhye*.
[src:amazake/amazake] In grape winemaking, must – sweet, thick, unfermented grape juice – is a similar product.
[src:amazake/andong-soju] Today, the rice wine for distilled soju is usually fermented for about 15 days.
[src:amazake/andong-soju] The process of making the fermentation starter (*nuruk*) for Andong soju consists of washing and drying wheat, which is then crushed and mixed with water.
[src:amazake/andong-soju] After, it is filtered, fermented, mixed with hard-boiled rice, and placed in a jug with water for about 15 days.
[src:amazake/andong-soju] The aged liquor is then boiled in a *sot* (cauldron).
[src:amazake/andong-soju] A *soju gori* (two-storied distilling appliance with a pipe), and a cooling device are placed on the *sot*, and flour dough is used to make an air-tight seal.
[src:amazake/andong-soju] It is spread on the gap between the *soju gori* and the cooling device so that no steam escapes.
[src:amazake/andong-soju] When the aged liquor is heated, it vaporizes, and the vaporized steam is cooled by the cold water in the upper parts of the *soju gori*.
[src:amazake/andong-soju] This causes the vaporized alcohol to be condensed and trickle down through the pipe.
[src:amazake/andong-soju] The development of soju in Andong is related to the Yuan dynasty's movement into the Korean Peninsula during the 13th century.
[src:amazake/andong-soju] The Yuan dynasty's supply base was in Andong and was established to prepare for an expedition to Japan.
[src:amazake/andong-soju] Andong soju dates back to the Silla dynasty (668–935 AD).
[src:amazake/andong-soju] The distillation skill was developed by alchemists engaged in trade with Arab tribes.
[src:amazake/andong-soju] Evidence of relations between the Silla and tribes of the Arabian Peninsula includes warrior statues with nonlocal features and Persian glass found at Goereung (hangul: 괘릉; an ancient tomb of Silla in Gyeongju, Gyeongsangbuk-do).
[src:amazake/andong-soju] China had been drinking hard liquor since the Tang dynasty.
[src:amazake/andong-soju] With the close relationship between Silla and the Tang dynasty, it can be assumed that strong liquor was used in Korea since the Silla period.
[src:amazake/andong-soju] The artisans of Andong soju are Jo Ok-hwa (조옥화; 趙玉花) and Park Jae-seo (박재서; 朴栽緖).
[src:amazake/andong-soju] These artisans keep alive the traditional ways of making Andong soju through the Korean government's support for discovering traditional alcoholic beverages since the 1986 Asian Games and 1988 Summer Olympics.
[src:amazake/andong-soju] After the Silla period, the skills of making Andong soju were passed down in Andong.
[src:amazake/andong-soju] Jo Ok-hwa made and preserved this Andong soju, so she was designated as "Korean food grand master No.20" on September 18, 2000.
[src:amazake/andong-soju] Daughter-in-law Bae Kyong-hwa (배경화) and son Kim Yeon-park (김연박) continue the tradition.
[src:amazake/andong-soju] Park Jae-seo is a descendant of Pak Eung-ju (박응주), the originator of the Bannam Park clan.
[src:amazake/andong-soju] For preserving his family's tradition, Park Jae-seo was designated as "Korean food grand master No.6" in July 1995.
[src:amazake/andong-soju] Andong soju is the only specialty to have two Korean food grandmasters because Jo Ok-hwa and Park Jae-seo's way of making it and materials are different from each other.
